node.text:
No, it’s not a UFO – but it does look like one! This was the test flight of ‘Avrocar’ – a secret US Airforce hovercraft project developed in the 1950s during the early years of the Cold War.
​
With a diameter of 18ft (5.5 meters) and weight of over 3,000 lbs (1,361 kg), it was hoped the flying-saucer-shaped craft could travel at speeds of hundreds of miles per hour at high altitudes, though it managed neither. The underside of the vehicle featured a massive ‘turborotor’, effectively a giant fan powered by three jet engines, which aimed at the ground and kept it hovering in the air.
​
The US Army had hoped to develop it into a combat-ready helicopter, however the technology proved too problematic. The angular momentum generated by the turborotor was intended to act like a gyroscope, however, during test flights such as in this video, the vehicle had too many issues remaining stable.
​
In December 1961, funding for the project ran out, and the Avrocar project was cancelled.
​ 
Credit: Public Domain / IFLScience

Aside from being extremely cute, the Thorny Devil lizard has some pretty cool traits!
​
Commonly found in the arid scrubland and desert of Central and Western Australia, these lizards have an unusual way of walking involving frequent pauses, which is thought to help them stay hidden from predators. Thorny Devils even have some strange dining habits. Their mouths have evolved specifically to feed only on small ants, and because of this, they are incapable of drinking the way most other animals do.
​
Instead, these lizards will bury themselves in damp sand where they use special capillary channels to absorb moisture, and that water is then drawn up into its mouth. They can also collect water from wet sand by shoveling it onto their backs!
​

Happy #MicrobeMonday! Check out this fascinating microorganism captured by @jam_and_germs. 
​
​This is a Synchaeta, a multicellular organism that is seen swimming among golden algae colonies. Synchaeta reproduce asexually, meaning they don’t require fertilization to reproduce. The colorful algae are Synura, which occur as spherical colonies, with the cells positioned so that the whip-like flagella point outwards, which they use to roll around in the water by whipping them in synchronization. 

​Video courtesy of @jam_and_germs

Last month, an anonymous bidder won a seat onboard the first crewed spaceflight of New Shepherd, the ship that will take Jeff Bezos and his brother 100 kilometers (62 miles) above the Earth. The bidder has now canceled their flight, citing scheduling conflicts, having something more important to do that day than go to freaking space.

In a press release, Blue Origin revealed that the anonymous person will be replaced by 18-year-old Oliver Daemen. He will become the youngest person to go to space, while Wally Funk – also due to be aboard – will become the oldest, at 82-years-old.
​

It's true, Dr Wu's team nailed it, really! 🦖
​
​Via Twitter/Tharkibo

This week marks the tenth annual celebration of #MothWeek! Across the globe, people are invited to celebrate the ‘beauty, life cycles, and habitats of moths’, share facts, appreciate, and generally revel in how awesome these little critters are.
​ 
In these photos you can see the Atlas moth. With a wingspan of up to 27cm (10.6 inches), it’s the largest moth species in the world! 
Unfortunately for them, they have no mouths in their adult form and cannot feed. Instead, they live off energy built up during their caterpillar phase. These stunning moths only live for around 5 to 7 days, using this time to breed and lay eggs, before dying. Live fast, die young!
​ 
Do you have a favorite type of moth? Tell us about them!
​

node.text:
Happy #WorldSnakeDay! 🐍 Did you know that there are more than 3,500 species of snakes around the world, with around 600 that are venomous? Snakes can be found in every continent except Antarctica, and are one of the oldest creatures featured in different mythologies around the world.

Snakes eat many different animals including rodents, birds, and even pigs and monkeys because of their ability to separate their lower jaw from their upper one and swallow their food whole. Impressive!

While snakes are seen as dangerous predators, their numbers are still declining due to deforestation and climate change. World Snake Day aims to spread awareness of these fascinating creatures, highlighting how they can be extremely important for the ecosystem, and to promote the preservation of endangered snakes.
